name: Ben Hance
summary: Australian swimmer Ben Hance made headlines by breaking the world record in the 100-meter backstroke S14 event at the Paris Paralympics, earning him a gold medal. The victory came during a challenging time for Hance, who dedicated the success to his late father. Tim Hodge, another Australian Paralympian, also won a medal and called for increased funding for para-sports to support athletes like himself. Hance's record-breaking performance also served as a reminder of the transformative power of para-swimming, inspiring others to overcome challenges and embrace their disabilities. The Paralympic Breakfast Day Nine event showcased Australia's strong performance at the Games, with two gold medals going to Australian swimmers. However, there was also a controversy surrounding a disqualification in the swimming competition involving an amputee athlete.

name: Calsher Dear
summary: In an AFL elimination final, the underdog Hawthorn Hawks stunned the Western Bulldogs, booking their spot in the semi-final. Key to their victory was young forward Calsher Dear, who shocked the Bulldogs with his unexpected "self-proclaimed 'shock'" play and preparation. His performance drew comparisons to Hawthorn legend Buddy Franklin. Dear's highlight included a remarkable soccer-style goal at the MCG, leaving the Dogs "scrambled." The Hawks' success was also attributed to the "naivety of youth," as revealed by coach Sam Mitchell. Jack Ginnivan's iconic celebration was notably absent, highlighting the Hawks' focus on the present and their determination to make history. Their victory sent shockwaves through the AFL, proving that even underdogs with youthful exuberance can achieve greatness.

name: Astro Bot
summary: Critics have unanimously praised "Astro Bot" as an exceptional game, hailing it as the best game of the year. CGMagazine describes it as a "must-play" title, while Kotaku commends its ingenuity and innovation. TheGamer emphasizes its status as a masterpiece that transcends the limitations of a museum exhibit. Inverse hails it as a triumphant exclusive that the PS5 desperately needed. Shacknews applauds its bountiful galaxy of bots, and The Shortcut praises it as the game the PS5 has been crying out for. GAMINGbible declares it an all-time great of stratospheric proportions, and NextGen Player echoes this sentiment in their glowing review. The Guardian acknowledges the glittering ideas that make Team Asobi's 3D platformer a gem.
